qas.question: What division of dialects does Hokkien belong to?

answers.text: Quanzhang Division (Chinese: 泉漳片; pinyin: Quánzhāng piàn) of Min Nan

context: The term <b4_0>Hokkien<b4_0/> (福建; hɔk˥˥kɪɛn˨˩) is itself a term not used in Chinese to refer to the dialect, as it simply means <a0_0><b8_0>Fujian province<b8_0/><a0_0/>. In Chinese linguistics, these dialects are known by their classification under the <a1_0><b5_0>Quanzhang Division<b5_0/> (Chinese: 泉漳片; pinyin: Quánzhāng piàn) of <b6_0>Min Nan<b6_0/><a1_0/>, which comes from the first characters of the two main <a3_0><b12_0>Hokkien<b12_0/><a3_0/> urban centers Quanzhou and Zhangzhou. The variety is also known by other terms such as the more general Min Nan (traditional Chinese: 閩南語, 閩南話; simplified Chinese: 闽南语, 闽南话; pinyin: Mǐnnányǔ, Mǐnnánhuà; Pe̍h-ōe-jī: Bân-lâm-gí,Bân-lâm-oē) or Southern Min, and Fulaohua (traditional Chinese: 福佬話; simplified Chinese: 福佬话; pinyin: Fúlǎohuà; Pe̍h-ōe-jī: Hō-ló-oē). The term <a2_0><b7_0><b11_0>Hokkien<b11_0/><b7_0/><a2_0/> (Chinese: 福建話; Pe̍h-ōe-jī: hok-kiàn oē;Tâi-lô:Hok-kiàn-uē), on the other hand, is used commonly in <b10_0>South East Asia<b10_0/> to refer to <b9_0>Min-nan dialects<b9_0/>.
